column1: #Text=For the Liu Song empress dowager , see Xiao Wenshou .
#Text=Empress Xiaoyiren ( died 24 August 1689 ) , of the Manchu Bordered Yellow Banner Tunggiya clan , was a consort of the Kangxi Emperor .
#Text=Life
#Text=Family background
#Text=Empress Xiaoyiren 's personal name was not recorded in history .
#Text=Her family originally belonged to the Han Chinese Plain Blue Banner .
#Text=Father : Guowei ( 國維 ; d. 1719 ) , served as a first rank military official ( 領侍衛內大臣 ) , and held the title of a first class duke ( 一等公 )
#Text=Paternal grandfather : Tulai ( 圖賴 ; 1606 – 1658 ) , served as a first rank military official ( 都統 ) , and held the title of a first class duke ( 一等公 )
#Text=Paternal grandmother : Lady Gioro
#Text=Paternal aunt : Empress Xiaokangzhang ( 1638 – 1663 ) , the mother of the Kangxi Emperor ( 1654 – 1722 )
#Text=Mother : Lady Hešeri
#Text=Six brothers
#Text=Third younger brother : Longkodo ( d. 1728 )
#Text=Younger sister : Imperial Noble Consort Quehui ( 1668 – 1743 )
#Text=Kangxi era
#Text=It is not known when Lady Tong entered the Forbidden City and became a mistress of the Kangxi Emperor .
#Text=She was first mentioned in official histories on 18 September 1677 when the Kangxi Emperor granted ranks and titles to his consorts .
#Text=She was granted the title " Noble Consort " .
#Text=As she was the only one among the emperor 's consorts to hold that rank , she did not receive a title to distinguish her from the other consorts .
#Text=On 18 March 1678 , the Kangxi Emperor 's second empress consort , Empress Xiaozhaoren , died so there was no one to take charge of the emperor 's harem .
#Text=Lady Tong was put in charge and became the de facto Empress .
#Text=On 13 December 1678 , another mistress of the Kangxi Emperor gave birth to a son , Yinzhen .
#Text=Traditionally , the Empress was tasked with overseeing the upbringing of all the Emperor 's children , regardless of whether or not she was their birth mother .
#Text=Since Lady Tong was the most senior among all the Kangxi Emperor 's consorts at the time , she was tasked with raising Yinzhen .
#Text=On 28 January 1682 , Lady Tong was elevated to " Imperial Noble Consort " .
#Text=On 13 July 1683 , she gave birth to the emperor 's eighth daughter , who would die prematurely on 6 August 1683 .
#Text=On 23 August 1689 , when Lady Tong was critically ill , the Kangxi Emperor officially instated her as Empress .
#Text=She died the next day and was interred in the Jing Mausoleum of the Eastern Qing tombs .
#Text=She was granted the posthumous title " Empress Xiaoyiren " .
#Text=Titles
#Text=During the reign of the Shunzhi Emperor ( r. 1643 – 1661 ) or the Kangxi Emperor ( r. 1661 – 1722 ) :
#Text=Lady Tong
#Text=During the reign of the Kangxi Emperor ( r. 1661 – 1722 ) :
#Text=Noble Consort ( 貴妃 ; from 18 September 1677 [ 1 ] ) , third rank consort
#Text=Imperial Noble Consort ( 皇貴妃 ; from 28 January 1682 [ 2 ] ) , second rank consort
#Text=Empress ( 皇后 ; from 23 August 1689 [ 3 ] )
#Text=Empress Xiaoyi ( 孝懿皇后 ; from 3 November 1689 [ 4 ] )
#Text=During the reign of the Yongzheng Emperor ( r. 1722 – 1735 ) :
#Text=Empress Xiaoyiren ( 孝懿仁皇后 ; from July 1723 [ 5 ] )
#Text=Issue
#Text=As Imperial Noble Consort :
#Text=The Kangxi Emperor 's eighth daughter ( 13 July 1683 – 6 August 1683 )
#Text=Miscarriage ( August 1689 )
#Text=In fiction and popular culture
#Text=Portrayed by Ha Chi-chan in The Rise and Fall of Qing Dynasty ( 1987 )
#Text=Portrayed by Zhang Xin in Palace ( 2011 )
#Text=Portrayed by Elaine Yiu in The Life and Times of a Sentinel ( 2011 )
